{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9f2d2570-e388-42f1-971b-faa7c942b258","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer workload packages needed by a newer SDK.\n\nAfter updating:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still get errors, check that `maui` (or `maui-android`, `maui-ios`, etc.) is listed in `dotnet workload list`. If missing, install it explicitly:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b2873d1-5094-4c73-9a2e-84361e6dfd11","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question that doesn't require any tool calls - I can answer it directly.","outputTokens":247,"requestId":"501A:1E6E:1811D10:1ACDEBB:69FA8F70"},"id":"c902c3be-e153-41b3-b48d-9b3270230eac","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:46:47.460Z","parentId":"eee6e450-ca64-4bf5-a2df-92597b986251"}
